----
Seven Sages of Ancient Greece:
1. Cleobulus of Lindos: 
> Moderation is best in all things
* Solon of Athens: 
> Nothing in excess
* Chilon of Sparta: 
> Do not desire the impossible
* Bias of Priene:
> Most men are bad
* Thales of Miletus: 
> Know thyself
* Pittacus of Mytilene:
> Know thy opportunity
* Periander of Corinth:
> Be farsighted with everything

----
Quotes by Socrates:
> An unexamined life is not worth living.

> Wonder is the feeling of a philosopher, and philosophy begins in wonder. 

> I know nothing except the fact of my ignorance.


----
Quotes on Diogenes:
> Aristotle dines when it seems good to King Philip, but  Diogenes when he himself pleases. 

> If you are to be kept right, you must possess either good friends or red-hot enemies. The one will warn you, the other will expose you. 

> Plato had defined Man as an animal, biped and featherless, and was applauded. Diogenes plucked a fowl and brought it into the lecture-room with the words, "Behold Plato's man!" 

> To one who asked what was the proper time for lunch, he said, "If a rich man, when you will; if a poor man, when you can." 

----
Quotes by Plato:
> Wealth is the parent of luxury and indolence, and poverty of meanness and viciousness, and both of discontent. 

> The knowledge at which geometry aims is the knowledge of the eternal. 

> Poetry and philosophy are always hostile to each other.

----
Quotes by GautamaBuddha:
> Conquer anger with love, evil with good, meanness with generosity, and lies with truth. 

> By not harming living beings, one is called noble.

> To cease from evil, to do good, and to purify the mind, this is the teaching of all the Buddhas. 

